column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was parked at the storage yard of the intermediate truck transfer facility.  During a routine yard check, it was noticed that a small amount of liquid was leaking from the trailer.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A drum was found to have a small leak in the side near the bottom.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with the absorbent material used to clean up the spill on the trailer floor and the pavement.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  The incident was called in to Ohio EPA, incident number 1204-31-0807.
column169: The leak appeared to have been caused by a small piece of metal protruding from the side and floor of the trailer.  The piece was removed and the area smoothed out.  Better trailer inspection prior to loading would have prevented this incident.  The origin location was notified.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  The Linden Bulk Transportation Co., Inc. vehicle was involved in a vehicle accident, which resulted in a rollover on I-78.  As a result, the tractor trailer unit straddled the center median of I-78, tractor landing on the westbound side, with the trailer in the eastbound lanes.  I-78 eastbound was closed as a result of the accident.  A valve on the cargo tank was damaged, causing a leak from an air-line, which released approximately 20 gallons of aluminum sulfate to the asphalt roadway. New Jersey DOT, Union County HAZMAT, and the Local FD responded to assess the site.  Local responders applied speedy dry to the affected asphalt roadway, and contained the release, pending cleanup and offload of damaged tanker.  Atlantic Response, Inc. of East Brunswick, NJ was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  The damaged tanker was offloaded, uprighted, and recovered from the site.  Additionally, there were approximately 5 gallons of diesel fuel that released from the tractor.  This was also contained to the asphalt roadway.  Atlantic Response, Inc. recovered all spent speedy dry from the affected roadway, and surface-scraped the contaminated roadside soils.  There was no impact or threat to state waters.  Seven (7), 55-gallon drums of spent speedy dry, and one (1), 55-gallon drum of contaminated soils were generated during response efforts.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the accident.
column169: Linden Bulk Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.    There was a witness that corobated the driver's statement to the NJ State Police that he was cut off and forced to take radical evasive action to avoid a collison. In addition, the driver was retrained in the Smith System Defensive Driving techniquies.

column168: The loading process of a tanker had just begun at the shipper's location.  The driver had completed a pretrip inspection with no issues, noticing that the tanker had just come from a certified tank wash facility.  The driver had routinely placed a bucket under the valve/hose connection and began the loading process.  The connection began leaking and the loading was stopped.  Most material was contained in the bucket but less than a gallon leaked onto the containment area.  The spill was contained with an absorbent material which was then placed into a drum at the shipper's location.  The driver disassembled the valve to see why it was leaking and found that the seal was missing.  He replaced the seal, reassembled the valve and continued loading without further incident.
column169: The tank wash facility had cleaned out the valve and reassembled it without replacing the seal.  The facility was told of this incident.

column168: Multiple shipments of hazardous waste had been picked up on a box truck and were being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.  When unloaded, some moisture was found on the floor of the trailer where 2 of the flex bins had been.  After donning the proper personal protective equipment, the bins were found to have small leaks where liquid was dripping out of them.  The bins were repacked along with the absorbent material used to cleanup the spill.  They were then loaded without further incident to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The material was described as a solid, but liquid content in the material had separated and leaked through small holes in the lining.  The profile was expired due to high liquid content and the shipper was notified.  IEMA was notified and assigned incident number H2012-0316.

column168: On 04/07/2012 at 1415 hrs., personnel in the Radnor Yard, Nashville TN. discovered UTLX 25389, a loaded tank car of Toxic Liquid, Corrosive, Inorganic NOS (Sodium Sulfate Solution) leaking from the bottom of the rail car. The car was isolated in track C1 of the rail yard away from CSXT employees and the shipper, Heritage Crystal Clean LLC, of Indianapolis, IN was notified via CHEMTREC report # 2012-04-07-00055. SWS Environmental Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene with a CSXT Hazardous Material Manager and found the bottom outlet valve was defective and the leak could not be stopped. Contractor personnel tightened the bottom outlet cap and reduced the leak to a trickle and deployed a haz-hammock. The issue identified was relayed to the shipper's  representative. The shipper provided 4 highway tank trucks to receive the transferred  product from the tank car. SWS Environmental also cleaned and purged the rail car of all residual product. The shipper will  request a OTMA to forward the car to a shop for repairs.     This incident did require a special switch move.     A 7.1 will be required for this incident    Cause Code:  544  NARRI:   5  ( 3+ 5+ 1 ) ( 2+ 0 ) = 90
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A van trailer was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation into various trailers destined for different waste disposal facilities.  Some material was noticed on the trailer floor that had also dripped onto the concrete containment area.  A response crew was summoned.  Upon arrival, they donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  It was found that the material inside the flex bins was wet and had caused the sidewalls of the flex bins to deteriorate and leak.  The material was repacked into a suitable salvage container along with the absorbent material used to clean the spill.  It was found that 3 of the bins leaked and all were repacked.  The shipment was then loaded into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.

column168: Cargo was rejected at the receiver for damaged cases - hazmat team brought in to secure cargo and made vehicle legal to drive.  Packages containing formalin (formaldehyde)were found to have loose lids; material spilled onto the cargo, damaging it.  No release outside of the trailer.  In discussion with shipper, the likely cause of the failure was heat; cargo not adequately protected from desert climate, resulting in a buildup of internal pressure that loosened the closure device (a screwtop lid).  The majority of the material from failed packaged had evaporated prior to arrival of hazmat team.   Residue and contaminated materials were disposed of as hazardous waste.
column169: Securement was sound; the failure point was in the packaging.  Shipper was advised to check the specs on their packaging; suggested fix is to protect cargo from the heat and use packages with higher spec seals that would be less likely to fail in the climate around Phoenix AZ.

column168: Tote tank was loaded at shipper's facility. Respirators were used by the folks loading the tote and explained to the drivers that the consignee would also use protective equipment due to fumes. Upon reaching delivery, drivers opened box doors and fumes were overwelming. Consignee suspected a leak. Doors were closed and local fire dept was dispatched on scene. Monroe Emerg Mgmt Team determined that cap used to close area for filling was missing. A rag had been placed into the hole instead of following the packaging requirements associated with DOT. Drivers never entered the box during the 43 miles of transit from the shipper to delivery due to the fumes experienced while the shipper loaded the container. FedEx contacted clean up company to come out clean up outside of freight container, neutralize floor of box and cap container to meet DOT transport requirements.
column169: Better Training. Package verification prior to loading freight container.

column168: CMTV was traveling southbound on SR220 approaching the intersection of SR220 and Wolcott Hollow Rd.  A 2002 Camry traveling eastbound on Wolcott Hollow Rd. did not stop at the stop sign and drove into the front of the CMTV causing it to lose control, collide with a guardrail system and then came to rest on a concrete bridge that crossed Wolcott Creek. Tank of the CMTV suffered  a slight crack (approx. 8")on the seam of the rear compartment and several puntures causing loss of approximately 600 gallons of diesel fuel.   Driver of CMTV was able to exit the CMTV and get the spill kit out of the truck to contain the spill.  Police and emergency responders were called in.  Company employees were also sent with additional spill kits and supplies to help contain the spill until ESP of Vermont arrived on the scene for clean up and remediation of spill.
column169: Accident could not have been prevented from any effort from company due to the nature of the accident.  Driver did all he could to right the truck before losing control -it was noted by witnesses that other vehicle made no effort to stop.  Crack in tank was out of reach (over the bridge) so spill materials could not reach the area that fuel was being released from.  Driver, employees and emergency personnel did all they could to contain the spill until the spill clean-up team arrived.  Our company was commended on how well we contained the spill by Emergency Personnel.

column168: Prior to unloading a Caustic Soda Barge the Terminal Operator failed to close a 2" water addition valve/hose connection that connected to the 6-inch unloading pipe.  This valve and pipe are inside of the tank containment area.  The Barge began unloading and some of the Caustic Soda entered this open 2" water addition valve/hose connection and spilled into the containment area.  Estimated flow time out of the 2" connection is one hour and five minutes.  When discovered the barge unloading was terminated and the 2" valve was closed.  The Terminal Supervisor contacted the Operations Manager.  The In-House Response Team responded gathered to begin the clean up process.  The Incident Commander/Operations Manager called the Minnesota Duty Officer and 911 to report the spill.  The spilled Caustic Soda was pumped into tanker trucks.  The cement containment area was cleaned and rinsed.
column169: A Pipe/Valve Walkdown/Checklist will be added to the procedures to be completed by the Terminal Operator prior to unloading barges.  This will ensure that all valves are positioned as needed to prevent future spills.    The Procedure will also be updated to include a pipe/valve leak inspection/walthrough after the barge begins unloading.    The Terminal Operator and Supervisor will be trained on the new procedures.

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained tank car UTLX 201037 dripping residue product from the bottom operated bottom outlet valve (BOV). A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder placed absorbent pads under UTLX 201037 and then inspected UTLX 201037. The responder reported that the bottom operated BOV operating handle was not pinned and not in the closed position. The BOV was closed and operating handle pinned in the proper closed position. The BOV's closure cap was found not in a tool tight condition and it was tool tightened ending the dripping. Afterwards, no further residue product drips were observed during a 25 minute observation period.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste at Clean Harbors Baltimore MD facility was enroute to its intended waste disposal facility. Plant personell noticed  that there was a leaking cubic yard box container (shipped under DOT-SP-11624). A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and unloaded the leaking cubic yard box; the cubic yard box was repacked. The trailer floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service for continued transport to intended disposal facility. The Maryland Department of Environment was notified of release.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. column14: RDI Warehouse at The Point Ind
column168: Dow Agrosciences in Midland, Michigan shipped three tanks full of spent carbon to RDI Construction in South Point, Ohio.  The tanks were not marked as containing hazardous material.  No failure or release of the material occurred.  Upon arrival at RDI, the material inside the tanks was tested and found to have a pH >12.5.  RDI management contacted Calgon Carbon, who contacted their customer Dow Agrosciences.  Calgon created a new manifest for the material, marked the tanks as containing hazardous material, and arranged to have the tanks shipped back to Dow Agrosciences.
column169: Dow Agrosciences must follow their procedure for flushing the tanks before shipping them to RDI Construction.     RDI Construction will continue to monitor the pH of material arriving in tanks from Dow Agrosciences and will not accept hazardous material or allow it to be removed from the tanks.  If hazardous material is discovered, RDI Construction will contact Calgon Carbon to have the material properly labeled and shipped back to Dow Agrosciences.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: Tank car GATX 53262 was reported in the railyard leaking product from the top manway area. GATX 53262 was carefully moved and isolated at a repair track within the railyard. A response contractor was summoned to inspect GATX 53262 and eliminate the commodity leak source. Responders reported that the installed manway gasket appeared chemically degraded as it was 'very soft' and tore easily. A new EPDM rubber manway gasket was applied and the manway cover was resecured and sealed. All other valves and fittings were found secure. No leaking commodity was reported impacting the ground. No further leakage was observed during subsequent movements in the railyard.   Intact seals at the valve housing cover and manway were replaced by seals numbered 652642 and 652649 respectively.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A TXDOT Rail Safety Investigator inspecting an outbound BNSF train in the railyard observed entrained tank car GATX 80659 with the top valve protective housing cover not pinned or sealed. Further inspection of the valve securement under the housing cover revealed an audible vapor hiss accompanied by a residue product odor emanating from the flange connection of the closed three inch liquid eduction line's valve. No residue product in liquid form was observed. Two of four liquid valve's mounting flange securement nuts were found not tool tight (hand tight only). A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder tool tightened the two loose securement nuts and during this process the remaining two securement nuts needed additional tightening. After securement was completed, no further vapor hiss was detected and this was confirmed by a liquid bubble test initiated around the flange connection.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A 55 gallon drum of UN1990 Benzaldehyde was punctured by a fork lift inside the trailer at 2901 Freeport Road, Harmarville, PA 15238 and released approximately 5 gallons of material onto the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the site to perform cleanup operations. The leaking/damaged drum was placed into an overpack drum for continued transportation. The environmental contractor also applied granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and swept up the impacted absorbents. All of the impacted absorbents were collected and containerized for transportation and disposal. No storm drains, waterways or surface grounds were impacted as a result of this release.

column168: During a routine load and tire check, the driver noticed liquid material coming from inside the trailer under the rear door.  The driver placed absorbent pads along the bottom of the door and called his supervisor.  A response crew was summoned.  Upon arrival, they donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  It was found that one drum had failed and most of the contents had leaked out.  A suitable salvage drum was used for the remainder of the drum and all of the absorbent material used to contain the spill.  The truck was then dispatched to the intended waste disposal facility 90 miles away without further incident.
column169: The drum was badly corroded and weathered and should not have been used for this material nor accepted by the driver who picked it up.  The driver was disciplined and reviewed proper container selection procedures.  The generator will be billed for the cleanup costs and has instituted procedures to more closely inspect drums prior to filling.

THE DRIVER GAVE THE AUTHORITIES HIS WALLET WHICH CONTAINED HIS SUPERVISOR'S AND HIS SPOUSE'S CONTACT INFORMATION, AND THE AUTHORIZATION CONTACTED BOTH.    MR.SIMON'S LOCAL SUPERVISOR, ALBERT CASTILLO, ARRIVED ON THE SCENE WITHIN AN HOUR AND CONTACTED THE COMPANY, STARDUST TRANSPORTATION LLC. SUBSEQUENTLY, THE COMPANY CONTACT ITS CONTRACTED AGENT, PERS, TO ENGAGE APPROPRIATE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE AS REQUIRED AND/OR NECESSARY. THE COMPANY SPOKE WITH LOCAL AUTHORITIES ON THE SCENE TO COORDINATE INFORMATION AND HAZMAT RESPONSE.     ALBERT CASTILLO ARRANGED FOR REMOVING THE LOADED PRODUCT, AND THE PROPERTY/ASSETS WERE REMOVED AND RECOVERED BY THE WRECKER COMPANY, LES MOTT WRECKER SERVICE.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMER LOCATION AND PROCEEDED TO MAKE HIS CONNECTIONS TO THE CUSTOMER TANK AND HIS CARGO TANKER. DRIVER BUILT UP HIS PRESSURE AND OPENED THE TOP ACTUATOR VALVE WHILE THE BOTTOM BUTTERFLY VALVE WAS STILL CLOSED.  THE FLOW OF THE BLEACH CAME TO AN ABRUPT STOP WHEN IT REACHED THE BOTTOM VALVE CAUSING THE PIPE TO CRACK AT THE FLANGE ABOVE THAT VALVE. DRIVER WAS SPRAYED WHITH BLEACH AND WENT TO THE EYEWASH STATION TO RINSE OFF.  HE RETURNED TO HIS TANKER AND SHUT OFF THE EMERGENCY VALVE WHICH STOPPED THE FLOW OF BLEACH.  THE CUSTOMER HAD ALREADY CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WHICH ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND WASHED DOWN THE AREA AND BACK OF THE TANKER WITH WATER FLOWING IT INTO THE SEWER. FOR PRECAUTIONARY ACTION THEY TRANSPORTED THE DRIVER TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT.  THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE CUSTOMER LOCATION AFTER BEING RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL WITH NO MEDICAL ACTION TAKEN.
column169: AFTER THE INTERNAL INVESTIGATION ON THIS INCIDENT IT WAS DECIDED THAT, DUE TO THE LOCATION OF THE FLANGE AND BUTTERFLY VALVE ON THIS TANKER, TO RE-PLUMB THIS TANKER TO UNLOAD FROM THE BOTTOM.  REVIEW OF THE UNLOADING CARGO TANKER SOP WITH ALL FLUID DRIVERS AND THE IMPORTANCE OF RELEASING PRESSURE AFTER EACH STOP.

column168: LTCX 1921 was reported to be releasing product from the valve box on the tank car.  Inspection of the car found the left side liquid valve completely open and unrestrained by a turnbuckle.  Liquid product was being released from the liquid outlet line as the cap/plug combination was not tool tight.  The valve was closed, stopping the release.  The turnbuckle was reapplied to secure the valve and the cap/plug was tightened.  No remediation was needed as the product was evaporating on contact with the atmosphere.
column169: Ensure valves are properly secured prior to releasing tank car for movement.

A Veolia employee was moving containers from one trailer to another at the Veolia ten day in-transit facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI. In doing so, the employee moved a pallet that contained nine 5-gallon pails containing coated spools of lithium metal ribbon in mineral oil. When the employee moved the pallet, one pail fell over and the lid popped off causing the release of approximately 1.5 gallons of mineral oil. The pail was immediately uprighted and the lid was placed back onto the pail. The spilled oil was cleaned up and using bentonite absorbent and placed into another container.
column169: Investigation of the containers post incident revealed that the pails were shipped with a secondary market lid called a gamma lid. Because the pails were not closed per the manufacturer's specification, all nine pails were then placed into salvage packaging before they were placed back into transit. In addition, the shipper was notified that the pails they utilized for the shipment did not meet DOT packaging specifications.

column168: Driver noticed a drip from rear of tanker and pulled over to the shoulder of IH10 and called emergency responders. Driver put on PPE to determine where leak was coming from. Noticed the drip between axles from flange area, tanker leaked a drip for approx 2 hours then stopped due to a vacuum created inside the tank. Sand was brought in to create a berm. Alamo 1, responded for Haz-mat team/cleanup but did not have the proper equipment for the job. SWS was called at 23:00. at 21:00 Tiger paws' second tanker arrived for the transload. SWS arrived at 01:52. Transfer began at 04:00, minutes after the pump failed. The trailer started leaking again but was contained in a containment pool and pumped back into the tanker. Transfer resumed at 06:45 with a pump provided by San Antonio Fire Department.. Lime was used to neutralize the spill and the ground would be scheduled for excavation as soon as possible. SWS decontaminated trailer with spill pads and lime for repair. Trailer was repaired by Tiger Paws mechanic to fix brakes, air lines etc for safe transport back to Houston. Upon examination of tanker after wash out, the liner appears to have failed causing the acid to seep around the flange at the sump area therefore causing corrosion around the flange, see pictures.
column169: Tiger Paw Transport leased the tanker trailer that failed. Tiger Paw Transport will no longer rely upon the assurances of the lessor regarding the condition and quality of the leased equipment and will have any leased equipment tested and inspected by a shop specializing in liners prior to placing any similar tanker into service. Additionally, Tiger paw has implemented a policy to retest and inspect the liners of it tankers for leaks and pressure every six months insteadof annually and Tiger paw's policy now requires a wash-out and visual inspection every 30-45 days.

column168: UTLX 201243 was reported to be releasing an odor near the East Bowl in the Neff Yard; Kansas City, MO.  Inspection of the car found a small amount of product had been released from below the liquid eduction valve.  Four of four mounting nuts securing the liquid eduction valve to the valve flange were not tool tight.  The nuts were tightened, securing the car, and the internal vapor pressure was relieved through the air valve.  The car was released to continue in transportation.  No other remediation was planned for this area as no product reached the ground.
column169: Ensure valves and fittings receive proper maintenance attention.

column168: THE 96 DRUMS OF MATERIAL WERE LOADED ONTO THE TRANSPORT UNIT. DURING THE LOADING PROCESS THE FIRST FOUR DRUM WERE PRESSED AGAINST THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  AS THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE LOADED THEY WERE PRESSED UP AGAINST EACH OTHER CAUSING ADDITIONAL PRESSURE ON THE BODY OF THE DRUM WHICH WAS AGAINST THE WALL OF THE TRAILER. THE VIBRATION AND MOVEMENT OF THE DRUM AGAINST THE TRAILER WALL ATTRIBUTED TO THE PIN HOLE LEAK IN THE SIDE WALL OF THE DRUM. THE PINHOLE LEAK WAS LOCATED ABOVE THE MIDDLE CHIME ON THE DRUM. THE DAMAGED DRUM HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE REMAINING THREE DRUMS IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER ALL EXHIBITED DENTS AND RUB MARKS FROM BEING PRESSED AGAINST THE TRAILER WALL, THESE THREE DRUMS WERE NOT LEAKING. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS REMOVED THE TRAILER AND PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON STEEL SALVAGE DRUM FOR CONTAINMENT.  THE SUBSEQUENT 2 GALLONS OF RELEASED PRODUCT HAD BEEN CONTAINED TO THE METAL FLOOR PLATE IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THE FREE LIQUID WAS ADBSORBED WITH ALL PURPOSE ABSORBENTS AND PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE LEAKING DRUM. THE METAL PLATE WAS THEN WASHED DOWN WITH SIMPLE GREEN AND WATER TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP.
column169: TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF A LEAKING DRUM, I WOULD SUGGEST SETTING THE DRUMS IN THE TRAILER VERSUS PACKING THEM IN EXTREMELY TIGHTLY. WHILE THE DRUMS ARE LOADED YOU ALWAYS NEED TO INSPECT THE CARGO TO ENSURE THEY ARE ALL STACKED CORRECTLY BUT NOT ONE PRESSED AGAINST ANOTHER SO TIGHTLY THAT IT CAUSES DAMAGES TO THEM.

Tank car CTCX 731577 was reported leaking product from the manway area during movement in the railyard. No ground impact from spillage was observed. CTCX 731577 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected CTCX 731577 and reported the shipper seal (0471425) on the manway closure was intact. Two of the six manway securement bolts were found less than tool tight with one of these out of position at the outer edge of the manway lid bolt slot. The manway gasket was inspected and found properly installed and serviceable. Afterwards, the responder properly secured all manway securement bolts and applied a BNSF seal to the manway closure. All spillage on the side shell evaporated. No further product leakage from the manway closure was observed during subsequent movements in the railyard.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: A BNSF crew pulling residue tank cars from a customer's facility reported that a crew member on the ground was splashed by contents emanating from tank car GATX 5842 and movement was stopped. The employee immediately washed off impacted area and required no pursuing medical attention.  Investigation by BNSF operating and mechanical/hazardous material responder revealed that an unloading pipe coupling/adapter was still attached to the top liquid eduction line pipe stanchion which would not allow the liquid line closure cap to be applied. The customer was in the process of removing this pipe coupling/adapter prior to the BNSF crew moving GATX 5842. Movement of GATX 5842 likely caused hydraulic surge of acid material in eduction piping to splash out through this open orifice. The pipe coupling/adapter was removed and the closure cap was secured on the eduction line pipe nipple. Spillage on the top shell of GATX 5842 was neutralized with baking soda and washed off.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings so that the transportation package is properly prepared for transportation.

column168: Transport was traveling southbound on CR1750 and entered eastbound curve onto CR22.  Driver attempted to decelerate just before and through the curve.  As the transport proceeded through the curve, the driver could not maintain his lane and encroached onto the unimproved shoulder of CR22.  As the trucks right side steer and drive axles entered the unimproved shoulder, the driver attempted to bring the truck back onto the paved road.  This caused the trailer to continue forward progress and subsequently overturn the transport.       Due to the rollover, the vent in the top of the CTMV leaked approximately 150 gallons of product onto the unimproved shoulder. Product was allowed to escape due to a damaged rubber vent line sleve.     OHP secured the scene and the Laverne Fire Department diked around the truck to prevent runoff.  Company personnel responded to the scene as well as an Environmental Clean-up contractor. Product in the rolled over CTMV was transferred into other CTMV's.  The rolled over CTMV was then uprighted via wrecker services.     The Environmental clean up contractor excavated the contaminated soil at the scene on 4/24/2012 and replaced with clean fill. The contamined soil was removed from the scene and appropriately disposed.
column169: The root cause of this accident was "Driving too fast for type of roadway", and the driver's failure to react appropriately to the leaving the roadway. Additional training is warranted.  All company drivers will participate in an accident review process to include the imporance of speed managment, and how to appropriately respond to the truck leaving the roadway.

column168: While loading ethanol from railcar to truck, product spilled from pump supply line on truck. Approximately 20 gallons contacted the ground inside containment area and pooled at puddle of rain water on the ground. Liquid was contained, did not contact any drains.
column169: Investigation revealed the truck was new and was configured incorrectly. Truck was equipped with pump supply line but not a pump. Butterfly valve blocking pump supply line was installed incorrectly. Butterfly valve appeared to be closed as handle was perpendicular to pipe. Pump supply line also was not capped thus allowing product to escape. The trucking company did not inspect their truck prior to putting into service. Moving forward, the company will require documentation from the trucking company indicating that trucks were inspected prior to being sent for loading and that all components are in proper working order.

column168: Local yardmaster reported an odor emitting from tank car UTLX 70600 located in track 7.  Inspection of car revealed the manway cover closed and 8 of 8 manway swingbolts in the down position.  Approximately 1 pint of product appeared to have leaked from the manway onto the sides of the car.  Additional residue product was also noted on the sides of the car from previous loadings.  8 manway swingbolts were properly positioned and wrench tightened which secured the car from further release.  The shipper made arrangements to have the car cleaned.  On 4-3-12 car was released to continue onto destination without further incident.

At the Birmingham TRANSFLO transloading terminal, a Trimac motor carrier driver started to transload Molten Sulfur from the cargo tank to railcar SHPX-209838 .This transfer was the first tank truck load of molten sulfur to be transloaded to this empty railcar. Soon after transfer started, the motor carrier driver noticed the product leaking from the unloading connection. He stopped the product flow and called over one of the senior employees at the TRANSFLO terminal to report the release. Spill pans and tarps were placed under the leaking connection to contain product. Once the product had stopped leaking the transload employee broke the connection and found that the gasket was intact, but noticed it had become unseated (misaligned) in the connection. Half of the gasket was hanging loose in the hose. This gasket has just been replaced a few days earlier. This was starting the 5th load on these gaskets and the gasket appeared to have been warped from the heat. The gasket was replaced and the driver tried to continue the transfer, but the product had solidified in the hose which required removal and replacement of the transfer hose. Approximately 1 gallon of Molten Sulfur was released onto the asphalt. It was all contained and cleaned up once it solidified. No product entered the facility drains or went off-site.

column168: Driver had used a pump to transfer the product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  When he was finished,he tried to clear the hoses the best he could without using air pressure because the product was combustible.  Unfortunately, there was still some product in the hose when he disconnected it from the trailer and less than four gallons ran out before he could get a cap on it. Driver had a bucket and spill pads down but most of it went on concrete.  The customer said they would hose it down their system.
column169: I discussed with the driver when he reported the incident and he said he didn't know what he could have done differently to disconnect the hose without a spill.  Drivers are trained in the proper procedure on clearing the hose when using a pump to unload.  Not sure if the pump wasn't pulling the product through the way it should have or the driver missed a step.

column168: After the cargo tank was loaded, the dome lid was closed on a small cable that was attached to the air line  and it's cap.  It was difficult to notice it.  When the driver stopped at our operating center in Dallas, he did a post trip inspection and noticed some leakage in the crash box.  That's when he checked the seal of the dome and noticed the cable was caught.  We got the okay to break the security seal put on by the shipper, opened the domelid, removed the cable and resealed the trailer. driver used spill pads to wipe up leakage.
column169: The shipper was notified of the issue to follow up with the loader.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN BOND WITH CUSTOMS. THE CONTENTS SPILLED ON TWO EMPLOYEES. THEY DID NOT REPORT THE AMOUNT SPILLED; WHAT'S LISTED IS A ESTIMATE. CUSTOMS HAD THIS SPILL CLEANED UP SO NO ADDITIONAL DETAILS ARE KNOWN EXCEPT THERE WERE 3 METAL CANS INSIDE A FIBERBOARD BOX. FAA JANET MCLAUGHLIN WAS NOTIFIED. THERE IS NO COMPETENT AUTHORITY LISTED FOR TANZANIA SO WE HAD NO ONE TO REPORT THIS TO VERBALLY THERE. AS THE OUTER PACKAGE HAD NOT BEEN OFFERED AS A DG  IT'S BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED OR HIDDEN DG. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER WHICH CLEARLY INDICATED IT WAS UN 3265, CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC ORGANIC N.O.S. CLASS 8, PACKING GROUP II AND THE TECHNICAL NAME.

column168: This shipment was questioned at origin due to the perfume description for customs. I asked them to open the shipment to see if they said flammable or not as a Material Safety Data Sheet was not with it. The inner bottles said flammable. As the outer package was not offered by the shipper with any dangerous goods markings, labels, nor with a shipper's declaration for dangerous goods it's believed to be undeclared or hidden DG. The FAA was notified and FedEx held the shipment pending their investigation.

column168: ON APRIL 19TH 2012 AT APPROX. 8100, OUR FUEL SERVICE TRUCK WAS DELIVERING FUEL TO A JOB SITE IN MOORHEAD, MN. (34TH ST AND 28TH AVE. S.). SERVICE TRUCK OPERATOR ENGAGED PUMP TO FUEL PIECE OF CONSTRUCTION EQUIPMENT WHEN A BY STANDER NOTICE FUEL SPILLING ON THE OTHER SIDE OF SERVICE TRUCK, BY THE BYSTANDER GOT ATTENTION OF SERVICE TRUCK OPERATOR AND HE DISENGAGED PUMP. (THE FUEL RELEASE WAS APPROX. < 2 MINUTES IN LENGTH). OUR CONSTRUCTION CREWS WORKING ON THAT PROJECT WERE ABLE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL USING MATERIAL ON THE SITES (SAND & GRAVEL). WE CALL THE CITY OF MOORHEAD STREET DEPT AND THE MOORHEAD FIRE DEPT WHO ARRIVE ON SCENE AND EVALUATED THE SPILL SITUATION. WE CONTINUED CLEAN-UP PROCESS AND REMOVED FUEL, WATER AND BASE MATERIAL USED FOR CONTAINMENT TO APPROPRIATE HAZ MAT FACILITY.  IT WAS DETERMINED SPILL OCCURRED BECAUSE OF A BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BEING LEFT OPEN AND UNCAPPED DURING A RECENT INSPECTION CONDUCTED ON THE 17TH OF APRIL. OUR OPERATOR DID NOT DISCOVER THE VALUE IN HIS DAILY WALK AROUND THAT MORNING.
column169: WE MADE IT VERY CLEAR TO OUR OPERATOR/DRIVER OF SERVICE TRUCK ABOUT THE IMPORTANCE OF A PRETRIP INSPECTION. SPECIFICALLY FOCUS ON VALVE CHECK IN PERIODS FOLLOWING A CONTAINER TEST AND INSPECTION.  WE ALSO CONTACTED THE FACILITY THAT PERFORMED THE INSPECTION AND ASKED THAT THEY CHANGE THEIR PROCEDURES TO NOTIFY CUSTOMERS OF OPEN VALVES FOLLOWING TESTING. STEERING WHEEL TAGS AND TAG ON PUMP HANDLE WERE DISCUSSED.

column168: At 8:50A.M. Mr. Yost spoke to Mr. Rony Robinson of the Amarillo Fire Department. It was reported that a shop mechanic had some of the liquid from the trailer get on his gloves and when he was power washing one of his gloves caught on fire creating a quick flash fire that burned his hand. The Fire Department responded and then made entry into the trailer and identified a pallet which contained multiple containers of Paint Related Material (acetone) which had one 5-gallon pail which appeared to have been leaking.    The pallet was located approximately 10 feet up into the trailer. Mr. Robinson stated that the spill was contained and there was no risk of an additional release. He agreed to leave the back doors of the trailer open so it would air out while EMI was enroute. The Fire Department then demobilized from the site.    The EMI team arrived on site at 2:00P.M.  EMI entered the trailer using Level C ppe and checked the air quality inside the trailer. It appeared that most of the acetone had evaporated and respiratory protection was no longer needed. They found one 5-gallon pail of Platinum Refinish Gun Wash on the bottom row of the pallet which had a crease that had split open on the side of the pail ncar the top of the pail. This damage was on the side of the pail that was facing outward and could not have been caused by anything on the load. The only assumption was the pail had to have been damaged during or prior to loading. Only 1-2 quarts of material could have been released from this crease. Their was also a hole in the side of the pail near the bottom that had been caused by it rubbing up against the adjacent pail. This hole was on the side of the pail which was facing towards the inside of the pallet. The boards on the pallet were fairly thin and were spread out so there was 3-4 inches of space between each of the boards. The pails sitting on the pallet were able to lean and shift back and forth during transit causing a rubbing action which wore a hole in the bottom of the pail. Several of the other pails had similar marks on them where the paint had been rubbed off of them.    The pails were removed from the saturated pallet and all were wiped clean of the acetone residue. They were then placed back onto a new pallet. A layer of all absorbent pad was place on top of the new pallet and a layer of cardbord was placed between each row of pails. Each row was secured tightly with cord and then with shrink wrap so they could not vibrate or wiggle side to side. The complete pallet was then shrink wrapped together so it was could not shift. The plywood separators were placed back inbetween the cargo and all of the pallets restacked back into the trailer prior to it being released.    Mr. Daniel Garcia, the truck service general manager, requested an MSD sheet of the released product to be sent to him and provided a fax number. He was requesting the MSD sheet since his employee had some of the material get on his hand. Mr.Yost obtained the MSD
column169: The pails on the pallet were improperly secured to the pallet and themselves allowing them to move and rub against each other. Also the container was either damaged during loading or prior to loading the trailer.    The hole in the bottom of the pail could have been prevented by proper packaging prior to transport.

column168: The  Austin vehicle (a truck tractor in combination with a van semi-trailer) was eastbound on Interstate 20 in the right fane. Traffic ahead of the Austin vehicle slowed, apparently  due to a small right-of-way fire on the westbound side being attended to by public fire services.  Responding to the slowed traffic, the Austin driver slowed, turned on his ememency flashers and cued in behind the vehicle to his immediate  front following slowly at safe distance.  In his rearvlew mirror, the Austin driver observed a vehicle approaching from behind.  Although the emergency flashers were on, the Austin driver immediately pumped  his service brakes to further signal the on-coming  driver.  Seconds later, the on-coming vehicle, a commercial motor vehicle, collided at an angle into the rear left corner of the Austin semi-trailer. The Austin driver was in his safety seatbelt at the time of impact, and he did not sustain any injury.    Fire service personnel were on the scene very quickly.  Police arrived shortly thereafter. Fire services freed the other driver from his vehicle.  He was subsequently  treated and removed from the accident scene by EMS. The Austin power unit did not sustain damage, but its semi-trailer was disabled by the collision.    With fire services  immediately  on the scene and law enforcement  summoned, the Austin driver called CHEMTREC and his home terminal for assistance to transload all cargo from his disabled semi-trailer to another Austin tractt:wtsemi-trailer.  The Austin disabled trailer's cargo was checked by the Austin driver, and no damage was  observed. All cargo within the disabled semi-trailer was safely transloaded  to the other Austin semi-trailer by trained  Austin personnel.
column169: AIthough, this accident  appears on Austin's most recent MCMIS, it is clearly "non-preventable" based on the definition of a preventable" in 49 CFR 385. 3.  However. in an abundance  of caution, Austin requested an independent accident  reconstruction specialist to investigate the accident. He concluded  that the Austin driver could not have taken any countermeasure that could have averted this accident.    The driver of the other commercial motor vehicle was cited by law enforcement, but the Austin driver was not.  The company  that owned and operated the other commercial motor vehicle has agreed to reimburse  Austin for all reasonable costs and damages related to the accident.

column168: On April 11, 2012, during transport, the tongue of the anhydrous ammonia tank trailer broke, which caused the trailer to swerve violently side to side and roll over (safety chains failed). As the tank and trailer rolled over, the cage protecting the preSsure relief valve was crushed and the pressure relief valve broke off the tank, allowing the contents of the tank to be released. After the tank rolled over, the driver towing the tank called 911. The 911dispatch notified police and fire departments who responded immediately. Precautions were taken to ensure the safety of persons in the vicinity. Ms. Alison Manz of the IDNR and Ron Tvinnereim of Gavilon arrived at the site on April 12, 2012 and contacted Iowa One Call upon direction of IDNR. Ms. Manz indicated  that soil would need to be excavated and took samples of water from the ditch. Gavilon personnel pumped water from the ditch and applied the water on an adjacent field, as recommended by Ms. Manz (with landowner consent). Gavilon personnel created a small berm to prevent impacted storm water from reaching a nearby culvert. A hazardous material response contractor arrived on site in the afternoon of the 12th and excavated soil as recommended/directed by Ms. Manz and worked on the 12th, 13th and 14th to excavate impacted soil. The soil was placed on plastic and covered with plastic. Once the ground was dry enough, the hazardous material response contractor applied the impacted soil on an adjacent field (with land owner consent). The contractor backfilled with excavated area with clay and black dirt, planted grass seed and placed erosion matting over the area (upon direction of IDNR and county).

column168: DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF TRANSPORT UNIT (SKIDDED), ROLLOVER RESULTING IN RELEASE OF CRUDE OIL LOAD.    TALON ENVIRONMENTAL (EMERGENCY RESPONSE) PERFORMED CLEAN-UP, REMEDIATION AND REVEGETATION AS PER TX DEQ. TXDOT GUIDELINES, STANDARDS.      Per Supplemental Report    Driver had loaded trailer and was transitioning from the access road to the entrance ramp of the interstate. Driver felt the load "shift" and the trailer tipped to the right. The momentum of the shifting load caused the trailer to tip all the way over and pull the tractor over as well. Both truck and trailer subsquently rolled over into the grass on the right side of the entrance ramp and then “spun” 180° leaving it facing NB.  The tractor sustained heavy damage on the passenger side and the top of the cab split.  The trailer suffered ruptures in three places along the right side along the top and a long tear in the middle of the trailer.  Entire load was released (185 bbls) as result of rollover.

column168: ON MONDAY APRIL 16TH, 2012 AT APPROXIMATELY 10AM I ASKED DAVID NORRIS TO GO AND RELIEVE CHESTER DAVIS FROM FUELING THE SCHOOLS SO HE COULD GO DEFUEL A FRONTIER AIRCRAFT AT AEROTURBINE. DAVID CALLED ME BACK APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES LATER TO ASK WHAT TRUCK TO USE AND TO LET ME KNOW THAT CHESTER CHOSE TO STAY ON THE SCHOOL. I TOLD HIM HE HAD TO USE JR1 ON FRONTIER AND THAT THE FUEL STORAGE LOG SAYS IT'S EMPTY.    DAVID CALLED ME ON THE RADIO ABOUT HALF HOUR LATER TO LET ME KNOW THAT HE SPILLED SOME FUEL. WHEN I ASKED HIM HOW MUCH FUEL HE SPILLED HE DID NOT RESPOND. TIM BERGER DROVE DOWN TO SEE IF HE COULD HELP WITH THE CLEAN UP. TIM CALLED ME ON THE PHONE TEN MINUTES LATER AND ASKED ME TO TELL CHESTER TO DRIVE DOWN TO AEROTURBINE WITH ABSORBENT. I CALLED CHESTER AND HAD HIM STOP FUELING AT THE SCHOOL TO TAKE THE ABSORBENT DOWN TO DAVID AND HE DID SO RIGHT AWAY.    CHESTER CAME BACK TO GET MORE ABSORBENT AND LET ME KNOW THAT IT WAS NOT A MINOR SPILL AND I BEGAN TO PULL PAPERWORK SHOWING WHAT FUEL WAS INVOLVED.
column169: SEE ATTACHMENT B. THE EMPLOYEE AT FAULT NO LONGER IS IN LUX AIR'S EMPLOY. AFTER THE SPILL, OUR DEFUEL/REFUEL PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH THE ENTIRE STAFF, WHICH INCLUDED A REMINDER THAT THESE PROCEDURES ARE POSTED IN EACH DEFUEL VEHICLE.

column168: ACCIDENT - 04-07-12 2302 HOURS  DRIVER STATEMENT    4-7-2012 TRAVELING WEST ON HWY 134 JUST PAST THE I-5 TURN OFF AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00PM, A SMALL CAR DARK IN COLOR HIT MY TRAILER. I DID NOT SEE THE COLLISION AS I WAS IN A TRANSITION WITH A TURN IN THE ROAD APPROCHING. I FELT THE HIT AND AS I LOOKED TO SEE WHAT HAPPENED, I SAW THE CAR THAT HIT THE TRAILER SPINNING SIDEWAYS IN A CLOCKWISE DIRECTION PASSING ME AT ABOUT 15-25MPH FASTER THAN MYSELF, WHICH I HAD CRUISE CONTROL SET AT 55MPH. AS THE CAR PASSING ME IN A SPIN HAD MY ATTENTION, I SAW A BRIGHT FLASH AND I LOOKED IN THE LEFT SIDEVIEW MIRROR AND SAW THE REAR TRAILER ON ITS SIDE AND ENGULFED IN FLAMES. MY FIRST THOUGHT WAS TO STOP THE TRUCK, SO WHEN I PRESSED THE BRAKE PEDAL, I HAD NO BRAKES. WHEN THE TRAILER ROLLED, THE AIR LINES WERE DISCONNECTED, LEAVING NO AIR PRESSURE TO CONTROL THE BRAKES, WHICH ALSO WOULD NOT ALLOW THE CRUISE CONTROL TO RELEASE. (CONTROLLED BY AIR VALVE IN BRAKE LINE). I CAN'T REMEMBER IF I USED THE CLUTCH OR TURNED THE CRUISE OFF VIA SWITCH OR BOTH. I HAD TO STOP THE TRUCK. WHEN THE TRUCK FINALLY STOPPED, THE OTHER CAR INVOLVED HAD JUST STOPPED IN FRONT OF THE TRUCK APPROX. 25 FEET. KNOWING THE REAR TRAILER WAS ON FIRE, I KNEW I DIDN'T HAVE MUCH TIME, SO I GRABBED A FEW PERSONAL ITEMS, UNBUCKLED MY SEAT BELT AND GOT OUT AS QUICK AS I COULD BEFORE I GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK I DID SEE THE MAN GET OUT OF THE DRIVER SIDE AND HELP HIS "FIANCE" OUT OF THE PASSENGER SIDE. WHEN I GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK, THE MAN KEPT ASKING ME WHY DID I COME OVER ON HIM, ACCUSING ME OF DRIFTING OUT OF MY LANE. I TOLD HIM I DIDN'T LEAVE MY LANE, AND THAT HE HIT ME. HE CONSISTANTLY WANTED TO ARGUE, BUT MY CONCERN WAS GETTING AWAY FROM THE WRECK KNOWING IT WOULD BE AN INFERNO IN MINUTES.    AS THE MAN WANTED TO ARGUE, I WOULDN'T LISTEN TO HIM AND TOLD THEM BOTH TO RUN THAT WAS GASOLINE BURNING AND WE NEEDED TO GET AWAY. THE MAN KEPT YELLING AT ME AS WE WERE GETTING AWAY. I LOOKED BACK AT THE TRUCK BEFORE WE WENT AROUND THE CURVE TO SEE THE FIRST TRAILER AND THE TRACTOR WERE BEGINNING TO CATCH FIRE, AND FLOWING GAS WAS BURNING, AND COMING IN OUR DIRECTION. I KEPT WALKING, LEADING US TO A SAFE AREA A FEW HUNDRED YARDS AWAY, STOPPING AT THE Z00 DRIVE EXIT, WHERE WE WAITED ALMOST AN HOUR BEFORE ANY LAW ENFORCEMENT CAME TO TALK TO US. AFTER WE STOPPED, APPROXIMATELY 5-10 MINUTES, A VEHICLE STOPPED (DARK RANGE ROVER) AND SAT IN THE FAST LANE AS IF HE WAS WATCHING THE TRUCK BURN. HE SAT THERE FOR ABOUT 10 MINUTES, THEN PULLS OVER TO WHERE WE WERE STANDING AND GETS OUT AND TALKS TO THE MAN THAT HIT ME. HE ASKED IF WE WERE ALL OK, THEN HELD CONVERSATION FOR A FEW MINUTES WITH THE OTHER GUY IN A LANGUAGE I DIDN'T UNDERSTAND. AFTER THEIR CONVERSATION, "JACK" AS HE INTRODUCED HIMSELF AS (THE MAN DRIVING THE CAR) SAID THE MAN IN THE RANGE ROVER WAS TRAVELING BEHIND ME AND SAW ME SWERVE INTO THE CAR. column168: ACCIDENT - 04-07-12 2302 HOURS  DRIVER STATEMENT    4-7-2012 TRAVELING WEST ON HWY 134 JUST PAST THE I-5 TURN OFF AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00PM, A SMALL CAR DARK IN COLOR HIT MY TRAILER. I DID NOT SEE THE COLLISION AS I WAS IN A TRANSITION WITH A TURN IN THE ROAD APPROCHING. I FELT THE HIT AND AS I LOOKED TO SEE WHAT HAPPENED, I SAW THE CAR THAT HIT THE TRAILER SPINNING SIDEWAYS IN A CLOCKWISE DIRECTION PASSING ME AT ABOUT 15-25MPH FASTER THAN MYSELF, WHICH I HAD CRUISE CONTROL SET AT 55MPH. AS THE CAR PASSING ME IN A SPIN HAD MY ATTENTION, I SAW A BRIGHT FLASH AND I LOOKED IN THE LEFT SIDEVIEW MIRROR AND SAW THE REAR TRAILER ON ITS SIDE AND ENGULFED IN FLAMES. MY FIRST THOUGHT WAS TO STOP THE TRUCK, SO WHEN I PRESSED THE BRAKE PEDAL, I HAD NO BRAKES. WHEN THE TRAILER ROLLED, THE AIR LINES WERE DISCONNECTED, LEAVING NO AIR PRESSURE TO CONTROL THE BRAKES, WHICH ALSO WOULD NOT ALLOW THE CRUISE CONTROL TO RELEASE. (CONTROLLED BY AIR VALVE IN BRAKE LINE). I CAN'T REMEMBER IF I USED THE CLUTCH OR TURNED THE CRUISE OFF VIA SWITCH OR BOTH. I HAD TO STOP THE TRUCK. WHEN THE TRUCK FINALLY STOPPED, THE OTHER CAR INVOLVED HAD JUST STOPPED IN FRONT OF THE TRUCK APPROX. 25 FEET. KNOWING THE REAR TRAILER WAS ON FIRE, I KNEW I DIDN'T HAVE MUCH TIME, SO I GRABBED A FEW PERSONAL ITEMS, UNBUCKLED MY SEAT BELT AND GOT OUT AS QUICK AS I COULD BEFORE I GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK I DID SEE THE MAN GET OUT OF THE DRIVER SIDE AND HELP HIS "FIANCE" OUT OF THE PASSENGER SIDE. WHEN I GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK, THE MAN KEPT ASKING ME WHY DID I COME OVER ON HIM, ACCUSING ME OF DRIFTING OUT OF MY LANE. I TOLD HIM I DIDN'T LEAVE MY LANE, AND THAT HE HIT ME. HE CONSISTANTLY WANTED TO ARGUE, BUT MY CONCERN WAS GETTING AWAY FROM THE WRECK KNOWING IT WOULD BE AN INFERNO IN MINUTES.    AS THE MAN WANTED TO ARGUE, I WOULDN'T LISTEN TO HIM AND TOLD THEM BOTH TO RUN THAT WAS GASOLINE BURNING AND WE NEEDED TO GET AWAY. THE MAN KEPT YELLING AT ME AS WE WERE GETTING AWAY. I LOOKED BACK AT THE TRUCK BEFORE WE WENT AROUND THE CURVE TO SEE THE FIRST TRAILER AND THE TRACTOR WERE BEGINNING TO CATCH FIRE, AND FLOWING GAS WAS BURNING, AND COMING IN OUR DIRECTION. I KEPT WALKING, LEADING US TO A SAFE AREA A FEW HUNDRED YARDS AWAY, STOPPING AT THE Z00 DRIVE EXIT, WHERE WE WAITED ALMOST AN HOUR BEFORE ANY LAW ENFORCEMENT CAME TO TALK TO US. AFTER WE STOPPED, APPROXIMATELY 5-10 MINUTES, A VEHICLE STOPPED (DARK RANGE ROVER) AND SAT IN THE FAST LANE AS IF HE WAS WATCHING THE TRUCK BURN. HE SAT THERE FOR ABOUT 10 MINUTES, THEN PULLS OVER TO WHERE WE WERE STANDING AND GETS OUT AND TALKS TO THE MAN THAT HIT ME. HE ASKED IF WE WERE ALL OK, THEN HELD CONVERSATION FOR A FEW MINUTES WITH THE OTHER GUY IN A LANGUAGE I DIDN'T UNDERSTAND. AFTER THEIR CONVERSATION, "JACK" AS HE INTRODUCED HIMSELF AS (THE MAN DRIVING THE CAR) SAID THE MAN IN THE RANGE ROVER WAS TRAVELING BEHIND ME AND SAW ME SWERVE INTO THE CAR. I DIDN'T BELIEVE THE STORY BECAUSE THERE WERE NO OTHER VEHICLES IN THE VICINITY AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT. WHILE WA

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 11:45AM ON SATURDAY, APRIL 7, 2012, A TANKER (CARRYING 10,900 GALLSONS OF GASOLINE) WAS TRAVELLING EASTBOUND ON I-278 IN THE BRONX, WHEN IT ROLLED OVER OFF THE ROAD ONTO THE MEDIAN OF THE SOUTHBOUND ON RIGHT LANE OF I-678. EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES AND A PRIVATE SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED. BY THE TIME THE LEAK WAS STOPPED APPROXIMATELY 5,900 GALLONS HAD SPILLED ON THE MEDIAN SOIL, SOME ENTERED A STORM DRAIN. THE STORM DRAIN WAS FLUSHED WITH THE EFFUGMT BRUSHES SOIL CONTAIMATED REMOVED FROM THE SITE ON THE DAY OF THE SPILL APPROXIMATELY 3,200 GALLONS OF THE SPILLED GASOLINE.  THE HAZMAT & VENTICAL EXCEPT OF CONTAMINATION WAS DELIVERED BY ENVIRONMENTAL PROFESSIONALS WHO WORKED WITH NYSDEC OFFICIALS OVER THE NEXT 3-4 WEEKS TO OVERSEE THE EXCAVATION OF 4,039.80 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL THAT WAS TRANSPORTED OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL AND THE FULL RESTORATION OF THE MEDIAN.IT WAS NOTED THAT NONE OF THE SPILLED GASOLINE CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE INTERSTATE HIGHWAY. APPROVAL TO BACKFILL THE SPILL STATES EXCAVATION WAS CLEAN BACKSPILL WAS SAVED BY THE NYSDEC AFTER REVIEW OF LAB RESULTS FOR THE CLEAR CONSTRUCTION SITE SAMPLES FROM THE EXCAVATION BASE AND STDG WALLS.
column169: THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT WAS DETERMINE TO BE "DRIVER ERROR". THE DRIVER WAS PROMPTLY TERMINATED. FINALLY, CROWN PETROLEUM ALSO INSTALLED GPS DEVICES IN ALL OF THEIR TRUCKS TO MONITOR THE LOCATION AND SPEED OF ALL OF THE TRUCKS.

column168: Product was transferred from the tote to another tote inside the trailer. Material on the street was cleaned with absorbent. A total of about 55 gallons was lost out of the tote. We estimate that about 5 gallons went into the sewer drain before the fire department was able to dike the drain. Per request of the Carrollton Environmental Agency the drain was flushed with about 800 gallons of water and was vacuumed out of the drain located further east. No citations were issued by the environmental agency or the police for the release. Driver did receive a DOT inspection after the cleanup and was put out of service for his trailer brakes being out of adjustment. W&B was sent to the scene to adjust the brakes on the trailer and the truck returned to the facility. Driver did complain about his eyes being irritated at the scene but stated he did not need to go to the clinic at that time. Driver did not need any medical assistance for this incident. No other reports of injuries has been made due to this incident    1. Driver arrived at first stop and opened the trailer door and identified a strong ammonia smell.  2. Stepped to the driver’s side of the trailer and identified liquid leaking from the front of the trailer.   3. Driver pulled away from the customers dock and onto the street and called incident into the facility.  4. Facility called ES&H and the fire department to initiate response to the incident.  5. Facility sent a 3 man crew to the scene to assist in spill cleanup.  6. 55 gallons of ammonia was spilled before the tote could be transferred on site to new IBC.  7. Cleanup was conducted in conjunction with local ER and Univar Contractor EH&S.  Univar sent three people to site from branch to assist.  8. Post spill Driver was given a DOT inspection and received a citation for trailer brakes out of adjustment.  9. W&B was dispatched to the scene and the brakes where adjusted and truck returned to Univar facility.

column168: - A TANKER TRUCK OWNED BY ELLIS OIL COMPANY WAS OFF LOADING DIESEL FUEL AT THE MONTGOMERY CITY YARD WHEN THE BRAKES MALFUNCTIONED AND THE TRUCK ROLLED FORWARD, BREAKING THE SEAL BETWEEN THE TANK PIPING AND THE TRUCK'S DISPENSER. THE DRIVER SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF THE DIESEL FUEL FROM THE TANKER AFTER APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  - ELLIS OIL REPRESENTATIVES CONTACTED CDG ENGINEERS AND THE MONTGOMERY FIRE DEPT. THE MONTGOMERY FIRE DEPT USED ABSORBENT PADS TO SOAK UP THE DIESEL FUEL AND DAM THE SINGLE DRAIN LOCATED IN THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA. THE ALABAMA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT (ADEM) AND NRC WERE ALSO NOTIFIED. SAND WAS ALSO SPREAD OVER THE AFFECTED AREA. THE ASPHALT BEGAN TO ERODE IN THE AREA OF THE RELEASE. ON APRIL 10, 2012 CDG PERSONNEL REMOVED THE DEGRADED ASPHALT, WHICH WAS REPLACED WITH APPROXIMATELY 33 CUBIC YARDS OF CONCRETE.
